> <p><strong>Age:</strong> 61.</p> <p><strong>Appearance:</strong> Successful attorney turned fabulous successful author of legal thrillers.</p> <p><strong>That’s amazing! Because that’s exactly what he is! </strong>I know! I admire consistency above all else, don’t you?</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"fce18b79f74c611c6f5f748798a54715639801be\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/fce18b79f74c611c6f5f748798a54715639801be/0_0_1650_2550/647.jpg\" alt=\"John Grisham, The Tumor\" width=\"647\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Grisham’s new novella, about a man with brain cancer.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p><strong>Absolutely. So – has he got a new page-turner out? Set in the south? Powerless little guy or poor black family up against an evil corporation and/or insurance company refusing to pay for the illness/injury/damage they caused? Good battling evil in a courtroom presided over by an agglomeration of human error and prejudice known as “the judge”, who may or may not do the right thing in the end?</strong> No.<br /></p> <p><strong>What? </strong>No. That’s out the window.</p> <p><strong>Explain yourself. </strong>This is a 49-page novella called <a href=\"http://www.fusfoundation.org/read-the-tumor-by-john-grisham\">The Tumor</a>.</p> <p><strong>Uh-oh. </strong>It’s about Paul, a man with brain cancer, and Grisham has written it to raise awareness of a new treatment called focused ultrasound. <a href=\"http://www.fusfoundation.org/the-foundation/leadership/board-of-directors\">Grisham is on the board of a charitable foundation</a> that believes it is the best hope for future patients.</p> <p><strong>Is there not even an attractively feisty young woman who interns with the hero for free and leavens proceedings by her mere physical presence?</strong> No. But Grisham is giving the work away free.</p> <p><strong>Really? </strong>Yes. He says it’s <a href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/john-grisham-thinks-his-new-book-is-so-important-hes-giving-it-away-for-free/2016/02/22/99ed8b62-d677-11e5-b195-2e29a4e13425_story.html\">the most important book of his career</a>.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/dec/19/john-grisham-q-and-a\">Q&amp;A: John Grisham – ‘My most embarrassing moment? It involved the passing of gas in church’</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>Forgive me – he’s a good writer an’ all, but can we trust that he knows what he’s talking about when it comes to experimental cancer treatments?</strong> The book is the result of eight years of friendship with the neurosurgeon behind the development of focused ultrasound and the founder of the foundation, <a href=\"http://www.fusfoundation.org/the-foundation/leadership/the-team/10-neal-kassell\">Neal Kassell</a>. According to The Tumor’s introduction, there is “enough research to date to be very optimistic … But progress is too slow. There are barriers from regulators, insurance companies, even many in the medical field”.</p> <p><strong>Gasp! <em>There’s</em> my insurance company bogey! I knew he’d be around here somewhere! Kassell is the little guy! “Many in the medical field” don’t want their cancer money poached! Everyone’s got a secret, venal agenda! </strong>We’d better read the book. And then look at the stats.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2015/oct/31/ultrasound-cancer-research-hifu-bone-trial\">High-power sound waves used to blast cancer cells</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>Or read the book and then just re-read </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/nov/13/john-grisham-litigators-review\"><strong>The Litigators</strong></a><strong>, or something? </strong>OK, sure, let’s do that. That’s the one about the lawyer, right?</p> <